\begin_layout Standard
\align block
The predominant view of status in empirical economics is of a hierarchy
 of social ranks.
 While empirical studies often treat status concerns inherent in observed
 social ranks separately from economic concerns, the sociological literature
 also explores the link between status perceptions and economic goals.
 An important concern for the sociological literature has been to reconcile
 the subjective aspects of status with its objective aspects.
 The current chapter focuses on a particular structural basis for a dynamism
 linking economic and social goals using probability functions that determine
 the promotion and demotion of participants among rich and poor classes
 in an economy.
 The consumer behaviour in response to participation costs and income difference
s are then explained while considering a promotion probability driven by
 two characteristics of the consumer - social capital comprising of skills
 that can be enhanced with expenditure and raw-talents that are unaffected
 by higher expenditure.
 Assuming a diminishing returns to utility from wealth optimised by the
 consumer, we find that a rise in income differences provides more incentive
 to participate in status competitions.
 The solution also suggests only two possible states for the economy - one
 where both rich and poor strive for status and the other where only the
 rich consumers participate in status competitions.
\end_layout

