\begin_layout Standard
While the predominant view of status in empirical economics remains one
 that is based on hierarchy of ranks (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goldthorpeOccupationalGrading1975,wegener1992prestigeconcepts,goldthorpesociology2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), several attempts have been made in both sociology and economics to view
 status in a more dynamic framework (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "webereconomysociety1925,shilsDeference1969,parsonssystemsocieties1971,ColemanSocialTheory1990,wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Instead of treating status goals separate from economic goals, the presented
 chapter pins down a specific link between economics and social goals relevant
 for status consumption assuming an indirect (instrumental) effect of status
 on consumer wealth (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColeMaliathSocialNorms1992,postlewaite1998socialbasisinterdeppreferences"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A contrast between economic and social goals seems has received far more
 attention in sociological literature (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) - where the issue of reconciling subjective aspects of status (the effect
 of status differences on individual behaviour) with its objective aspects
 (the observed reality of status differences) has been explored in great
 detail.
 There seem two broad categories (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) which the various theories for status can be classified into - those that
 consider status as a hierarchical order (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parsonssystemsocieties1971,wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ) and those that consider it in terms of a conflict among social groups
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "webereconomysociety1925,wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Several approaches in economics have also incorporated views from the sociologi
cal literature while using a dynamism in the social order relevant for status
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes,moldovanuselacontestsstatus2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The current chapter relies upon one such view of status (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) - as a product of economic processes shaped by institutional nurturing
 or discouragement of individual attributes (also see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moldovanuselacontestsstatus2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Given the extreme variation of economic development that are observed across
 developing economies (such as Tanzania and Nigeria), the endogenisation
 of status in such a manner provides us a generic framework to compare disparate
 developing economies.
 
\end_layout

