\begin_layout Standard
To specify a structural relationship between the economic and social goals
 of an individual, the current chapter uses probability functions that define
 promotion to a richer status class.
 While the probability of promotion for the consumer is driven by her expenditur
e, the utility for the consumer comes only from her accumulated wealth.
 Our approach where participants do not consider the rich status directly
 into the utility (and therefore do not directly maximise the chances to
 be rich) - follows 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "postlewaite1998socialbasisinterdeppreferences"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 closely who also discuss the relevance of uncertainty in conspicuous consumptio
n.
 In the probabilistic game we use to represent status compeitions, the participa
nts compete both with raw-talent and acquired-skills (social capital) to
 get promoted to (or to maintain) a rich position.
 More specifically, the winner of the game is promoted to a rich position
 (or maintains her rich position) by having the maximum total score comprising
 both of raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 (uniformly distributed in a population) and social capital 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 (enhanced with expenditure).
 The social-capital 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 that is enhanced through expenditure is also subject to budget constraints
 imposed on the consumer
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We do not view leisure as separate from budget constraints in the model.
 In other words, the leisure relevant for higher stauts is interpreted simply
 as a higher cost for the poorer participant.
 So long as once can view leisure as the amount of money a participant must
 forgo in order to participate in status competition, the leisure differences
 can be also viewed as differences in disposable incomes.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth emphasising that the only two types of participants in the tournamen
t view of status used in the current chapter are the poor and rich classes
 - so that the investments towards status (such as club-membership fees,
 or higher-education) increase the chances to be promoted to the rich status.
 Those who don't participate in the tournament certainly suffer with being
 poor, but those who do spend only benefit probabilistically.
 A useful analogy to explain such a competition is that of tennis leagues
 - where rewards are risky but are unlike lotteries in that more expenditure
 does not linearly increase one's chance to win in a tennis championship.
 As with the game of tennis, participants with appropriate raw-talent and
 skills may exist naturally in a population but their success also depends
 on engagement with other tennis players.
 More specifically, there may exist biological characteristics such as strength,
 dexterity, height or psychological abilities (resilience, conscientiousness
 etc.) that help one's tennis, but there also exist several characteristics
 such as technique, rankings, knowledge of conventions, racket-customisations
 that are only available at a significant cost to the participant.
 The enhancement of these latter skills (social capital) are what the institutio
nal support are meant to represent.
 It has been argued more generally that the characteristics of status games
 are often made to reward curated abilities rather than naturally occurring
 raw-strengths (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 of raw-talent in the maximum total score considered for the win, the consumer
 preferences for the probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu r_{i}+(1-\mu)s_{i}$
\end_inset

 ( where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is raw-talent and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 are skills that are available with higher expenditure) are considered under
 the assumption that the participants maintain the population constant over
 time.
 The rich participants are thus replaced by either a rich or poor participant
 only through the tournament that selects highest combined score regardless
 of rich or poor background of the participant.
 Since all participants participate in every such tournament, it is possible
 for a rich participant to lose her rich-position and let another participant
 acquire her position.
 We also assume that the preferences for all poor participants are the same
 as are the preferences of all the rich participants.
 Having a rich or a poor status by itself only has an indirect effect (through
 higher expenditure or budget) on the chance to be promoted (or maintaining
 one's rich position) - a probability that otherwise depends on the privately
 known ability 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and social-capital 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 All rich participants and all poor participants having the same behaviour
 also means that the privately known attributes 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 are not used by the participant to decide upon the expenditure (effort)
 towards the status game.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that if the rich and poor participants have disparate incomes 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 (so that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}<y_{2}$
\end_inset

), then the above setup evidently puts the poor participants at a disadvantage
 since they may not afford to pay the costs to enhance their skills (i.e.
 realise the true worth of their skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 due to high participation costs).
 However, since both raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and social-capital 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 (the latter enhanced by costly institutional support) are randomly distributed
 in the population, the competition may never rule out the chance for a
 poor participant to win.
 For the same reason, the returns from investments to enhance one's skills
 may also be diminishing since one cannot beat raw-talent and non enhanced-skill
s after a certain point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to highlight that above status competitions are not meant
 to be population-wide tournaments that involve all participants of a society.
 Instead, the competitions are small-scale with varied locally defined criteria
 that may have multiple stages.
 All such competitions are meant to be independent and may vary only in
 the threshold participation cost and range of distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i},s_{i}$
\end_inset

 of the participants.
 As scope of the presented chapter is limited to the effect of income difference
s on consumption, we discuss only a particular competition with known distributi
on of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 among a relatively small number of participants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, a few properties of a game follow where a wealth-optimising
 participant with a maximum score wins by enhancing her skills (social capital)
 and using her raw-talent.
 First, only one player with the maximum score can win a particular tournament.
 Second, the rank of the participant (rich / poor status) is of no direct
 significance part of her utility from wealth.
 Lastly, the privately known raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 are of no significance to expenditure decisions - which vary solely on
 the basis of rich or poor status.
 A closed-form solution with a diminishing utility from wealth and a threshold
 level expenditure required for participants to spend in order to avail
