\begin_layout Standard
Status is often contrasted as a social goal of an individual against her
 economic goals.
 Yet the difference between social and economic goals of the individual
 remains unclear in both sociology and economics (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The idea that status is orthogonal to economic goals - or the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pure status
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 view (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moldovanuselacontestsstatus2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ) - seldom fits with the real-world where status both contributes to income
 and improves with rises in income.
 Indeed the other extreme view that the economic goals alone motivate status
 competitions - so that status is derived purely from economic rewards is
 also unrealistic.
 As 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "moldovanuselacontestsstatus2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argue, the reality is often somewhere in between the two extremes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A structural model for the interplay between economic and social goals is
 yet to specified in either sociology or economics.
 The dominant view for status in both sociology and economics has been based
 on hierarchy and social deference (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990,goldthorpesociology2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) - a view that is inherent in occupational status surveys widely used in
 empirical studies (e.g.
 the EGP classes or the Goldthorpe class scheme).
 A fundamental problem that the sociology literature has elaborated further
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) is the failure in empirical studies to reconcile the difference between
 objective aspects of status (the observed reality of status differences)
 and its subjective aspects (the effect of status differences on individual
 behaviour).
 An evident issue with addressing only the objective aspect of status using
 a utilitarian model while leaving the subjective aspect exogenous is that
 status may never be explained in economic terms when an economy for status
 is ruled out.
 As the literature in sociology warns, the idea of social-closure (aggregate
 or stände first discussed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "webereconomysociety1925"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) ought not be conflated with that of social ranks (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The issue is not a mere theoretical one.
 Empirical studies suggest that the subjective (private) evaluations of
 status often measure an overall desirability of occupations rather than
 common objective notions for status (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goldthorpeOccupationalGrading1975"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "adlerstatuscomponents1985"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find that skills or knowledge of individuals to be a better predictor for
 individual judgments of status.
 Lastly, the scales of status used in empirical studies are observed to
 vary significantly across the sections of a society as well (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ackerwomenstratification1980"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several approaches have aimed to reconcile the difference between objective
 and subjective aspects of status (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parsonssystemsocieties1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, for example, addresses the issue by simply ensuring that the subjective
 and objective aspects coincide in status-related interpretations.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parsonssystemsocieties1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argues that the basic categories in terms of which we describe a system
 of hierarchies as a structure is the same as those in terms of which individual
 behavior or performance should be defined.
 While culture places a premium on equality, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parsonssystemsocieties1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 argues, the distribution rules in different social subsystems are not aimed
 at generating equality - thus letting status exist to assert basic importance
 of equality of membership status while also making allowances for inequalities
 resulting from equality of opportunity (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wegener1992prestigeconcepts"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The bottom line of these arguments is that societies must institutionalize
 some balance between equality and inequality at all times (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parsonsInfluence1963,parsonssystemsocieties1971"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 discusses an economy of status where status is created as part of the economic
 processes while social institutions nurture or discourage certain naturally
 characteristics in a society.
 Instead of interpreting status items as those that signal hierarchical
