\begin_layout Standard
Other attempts to reconcile the subjective and objective aspects of status
 (and therefore of social-closure and hierarchy) use rational conflict-based
 arguments to specify the structural basis for status.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, for example, consider power (purportedly amounting to status) as a commodity
 to be exchanged in the economy - an approach that has drawn much criticism
 due to the zero-sum characteristics it imposes on status while treating
 the total status on a status society as fixed (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wrongpower1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The current chapter instead leans towards the view from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "goode1978celebrationheroes"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who had argued that as a product of exchange processes, status is likely
 to be available in ample supply in a society.
 To specify the processes that link the economic and social goals of the
 individual, the current chapter uses probability functions leading to hierarchi
cal promotion that depend on an 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
emph{a priori}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 distribution of personal attributes.
 Instead of using status as a wealth-determined goal, the presented chapter
 follows an approach suggested by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "postlewaite1998socialbasisinterdeppreferences"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to consider status only of an indirect role in maximisation of consumer
 utility from wealth.
 A similar model is implemented by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColeMaliathSocialNorms1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 where a participants have a concern for relative standing because of their
 standing being instrumental in determining ultimate consumption levels
 rather than being directly contributing to their utility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above probability function approach bears some similarity with the Tullock
 function used in contest theory approaches as well (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tullock1967"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Further developments in the contest-theory literature relating to multiple
 stage contests (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "parcorepoportamaldossTwoStageBudget2005,SteinRapoportsymmetrictwostagecontests2005"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and budget-constraints (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
