\begin_layout Standard
With a privately known raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and skills (social-capital) 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 - that are both uniformly distributed (the latter i.e.
 social capital enhanced with expenditure) - we consider foremost the likelihood
 of any participant 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in[1,N]$
\end_inset

 as the probability for their total score 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu r_{i}+(1-\mu)s_{i}$
\end_inset

 being higher than any other participant.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 is a parameter that combines skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 so that the participant with maximum score 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu r+(1-\mu)s$
\end_inset

 wins the competition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider that in a much simpler competition with raw-talents alone, the
 winning participant is one who has the maximum 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 drawn from the sample 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, the winner in a competition of raw-talents is a player
 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{r_{i}<r_{j}\forall i\in[1,N]\}$
\end_inset

 and the probability that a given participant 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 of raw-skill 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the winner is essentially that of all other players 
\begin_inset Formula $j\ne i$
\end_inset

 having ability 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{j\ne i}$
\end_inset

 less than 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This is the probability 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1}{P(r_{i}>r_{1})\times P(r_{i}>r_{2})\times...P(r_{i}>r_{i-1})\times P(r_{i}>r_{i+1})...P(r>r_{N})}dr_{i}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With a uniform distribution of skills 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $P(r_{i}\ge r)=r_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in[1,N]$
\end_inset

 and therefore, the probability is evaluates to 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}{(r_{i})^{N-1}}dr_{i}=\frac{1}{N}$
\end_inset

.
 With more players, the chances of a particular participant winning evidently
 declines.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Introducing the skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 which are curated in social institutions, we consider a threshold investment
 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 which is necessary to be spent for the social capital to be available to
 a participant.
 While this is an arrangement that evidently favours the rich participant,
 there are also diminsihing returns to investing 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 towards the richer position.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An imporant assumption in the foregoing analysis is that raw-talent is less
 valued than skills cultivated by institutions.
 As as result, we use the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\mu>\mu$
\end_inset

 (which is equivalent to the following assumption) in the rest of the discussion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Assumption
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "assu:mu_less_than_half"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mu<\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Worth highlighting that this is needed 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the threshold investment 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 as a discrete response to costs of participation, the participants face
 different probabilities to win depending on whether they spend 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 or not.
 More specifically, the participant takes advantage of the skills with weight
 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\mu$
\end_inset

 only when she spends an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 In the all-or-nothing payment scheme, the participant might avoid the investmen
t altogether and keep the investment towards savings instead.
 The behaviour of all participants depends only on 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1},\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 - as they are unaware of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i},s_{i}$
\end_inset

 before they participate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result we use depends on the following distribution function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\equiv\mu r_{i}+(1-\mu)s_{i}$
\end_inset

 under the Assumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "assu:mu_less_than_half"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
are independent random variables uniformly distributed between 0 and 1 (see
 Appendix A) .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
F_{X}(x) & =P(x_{k}<x)=P(r_{k}\mu+s_{k}(1-\mu)<x)=\begin{cases}
\frac{x^{2}}{2\mu(1-\mu)} & 0<x<\mu\\
\frac{x-\mu/2}{1-\mu} & \mu<x<1-\mu\\
1-\frac{(x-1)^{2}}{2\mu(1-\mu)} & 1-\mu<x<1\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the game where a participant 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 with the maximum score 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the winner, the number of rich positions is fixed to 
\begin_inset Formula $N-P$
\end_inset

 so that only the top-scorer gets to occupy the only rich position available
 to be filled in every competition.
 The expected behaviour of the rich and the poor participants in the long-term
 can be explained with four different cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Case I - The poor participant does not participate due to insufficient investmen
t 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 while the rich participant does participate by spending 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}=\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Case II - The rich participant does not participate with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 but the poor participant does participate i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}=\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Case III - Both poor and rich participants do not participate so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}=\nu_{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Case IV - Both poor rich and participant participate with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}=\nu_{2}=\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
