\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With Case I, the poor participant can win when her raw-talent (weighted
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

) is higher than the total score of all other poor participants as well
 as the total score of the rich participants (who compete with acquired
 skills).
 The poor are priced out of accessing any skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 in their score in Case I so that only the rich participants with investment
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}=$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

 have skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, a given poor participant must be ahead both of all of the poor participan
ts and the rich participants so that a participant 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 may win only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu r_{i}$
\end_inset

 is higher than than raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu r_{k}$
\end_inset

 in all poor participants and also exceeds the score 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu r_{k}+(1-\mu)s_{k}$
\end_inset

 involving skills among the rich participants
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
P_{1}(\text{win}|r_{i}) & =\prod_{k=1,k\ne i}^{P}P(\mu r_{k}<\mu r_{i})\prod_{k=P+1}^{N}P(\mu r_{k}+(1-\mu)s_{k}<\mu r_{i})=r_{i}^{P-1}F_{X}(\mu r_{i})^{N-P}\label{eq:CaseI_general}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P_{1}(\text{win}|r_{i}) & =\begin{cases}
\frac{\mu^{N-P}r_{i}^{2N-P-1}}{2\mu(1-\mu)} & 0<r_{i}<\mu\\
r_{i}^{P-1}(\frac{\mu r_{i}-\mu/2}{1-\mu})^{N-P} & \mu<r_{i}<1-\mu\\
r_{i}^{P-1}(1-\frac{(\mu r_{i}-1)^{2}}{2\mu(1-\mu)})^{N-P} & 1-\mu<r_{i}<1\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the uniform density for 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(r_{i})=1$
\end_inset

 ), total probability to win can be calculated as
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{r_{i}=0}^{r_{i}=1}P(\text{win}|r_{i})dr_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that since only one participant can win the skills-game, the probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\int_{0}^{1}P_{2}(\text{win}|r_{i},s_{i})ds_{i}dr_{i}$
\end_inset

 for a rich participant to win is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{N-P}-\frac{P}{N-P}\int_{0}^{1}\int_{0}^{1}P_{1}(\text{win}|r_{i},s_{i})ds_{i}dr_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Case II, when the rich person does not participate (i.e.
 all rich participants have 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}=0$
\end_inset

), the poor participant has the skills-advantage in the game so the the
 probability to win for the poor participant 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
P(\text{win}|r_{i})=\prod_{k=1,k\ne i}^{P}P(\mu r_{k}+(1-\mu)s_{k}<\mu r_{i}+(1-\mu)s_{i})\prod_{k=P+1}^{N}P(\mu r_{k}<\mu r_{i}+(1-\mu)s_{i})\\
=F_{X}(x_{i})^{P-1}\prod_{k=P+1}^{N}P(\mu r_{k}<\mu r_{i}+(1-\mu)s_{i})\label{eq:CaseII_general}
\end{multline}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Case III, when neither the rich nor the poor participate in the game,
 then the game depends only on raw-talents and all participants have the
 same probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{N}$
\end_inset

 to win the game.
 This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{r_{i}=0}^{r_{i}=1}P(\text{win}|r_{i})dr_{i}=\frac{r_{i}^{N}}{N}|_{0}^{1}=\frac{1}{N}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\text{win}|r_{i})=\prod_{k=1,k\ne i}^{P}P(r_{k}<r_{i})\prod_{k=P+1}^{N}P(r_{k}<r_{i})=r_{i}{}^{N-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Case IV, when both rich and poor participants set 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}=\nu_{2}=\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

, then the poor participant can win only if her score 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is above all other participants - rich or poor.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
P(\text{win}|r_{i})=\prod_{k=1,k\ne i}^{P}P(\mu r_{k}+(1-\mu)s_{k}<\mu r_{i}+(1-\mu)s_{i})\prod_{k=P+1}^{N}P(\mu r_{k}+(1-\mu)s_{k}<\mu r_{i}+(1-\mu)s_{i})\\
=F_{X}(x_{i})^{N-1}\label{eq:CaseIV_general}
\end{multline}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using symmetry arguments, this winning probability also turns out to be
 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

 for all the participants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth emphasising that the effect of expenditure on the winning probabilit
