\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Case I
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Case I, the poor participant can win when her raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 is higher than of the total score of rich participant (who competes with
 acquired skills).
 The poor participant is priced out of accessing any skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 in her score so that the skills 
\begin_inset Formula $s>0$
\end_inset

 is only true for the rich participant having 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $=\overline{\nu}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the poor participant with raw-talent 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}$
\end_inset

 can win with the following probability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P(\text{win}|r_{1}) & =P(\mu r_{2}+(1-\mu)s_{2}<\mu r_{1})=F_{X}(\mu r_{1})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu r_{1}<\mu<1-\mu<1$
\end_inset

 is implied due to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu<\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 ).
 The probability that the total score 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu r_{2}+(1-\mu)s_{2}$
\end_inset

 does not exceed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu r_{1}$
\end_inset

 implies that only the first part of the piecewise function for 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{X}(x)$
\end_inset

 needs to be considered.
 Therefore, using 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\text{win}|r_{1})=\frac{\mu^{2}r_{1}^{2}}{2\mu(1-\mu)}$
\end_inset

, we evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}(\text{win})$
\end_inset

 as 
